    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-05-06T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-05-06T00:00:00-05:00" n="1000"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1000">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 703.4112/5.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">British Embassy</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-05-06">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 6, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The Department of State has the honor to acknowledge the receipt of the note,
                    dated the 28th ultimo, from His Britannic Majesty’s Embassy, stating that, in
                    compliance with the Department’s request, Sir Edward Grey has directed Sir
                    Lionel Carden to instruct the British consular officers at Frontera, La Paz,
                    Ensenada, Colima, Salina Gruz and Acapulco to take charge of American interests
                    in the absence of French consular officers in those places.</p>
                <pb facs="0761" n="645" xml:id="pg_645"/>
                <p>In reply the Department of State has the honor to assure His Britannic Majesty’s
                    Embassy of the appreciation of this Government for this courteous action on the
                    part of His Majesty’s Government.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
